\begin_layout Standard
Overcoming unphysical pressure oscillations generated at material interfaces
 of multi-component flows has been one of the primary challenges in the
 simulation of chemically reacting flows.
 The source of these oscillations has been attributed to variations in the
 thermodynamic properties of multi-component gases.
 Furthermore, it was previously concluded that any fully conservative Godunov-ty
pe scheme would be unable to maintain a pressure equilibrium across material
 fronts
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Abg88"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, the original analysis assumed that the variable ratio of specific
 heats, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, was only a function of species concentrations and was frozen at each time
 step
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kar94,Abg96"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Jenny et al.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jen97"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also analyzed the conditions under which pressure oscillations are generated
 and concluded that the pressure remains in equilibrium across a material
 interface if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The interface is grid aligned throughout the time step.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:grid-aligned"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The ratio of specific heats, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, is continuous across the interface.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:continuous-ratio-of-specific-heats"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The temperature is continuous across the interface, i.e., discrete temperature
 equilibrium between adjacent elements is maintained.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:continuous-temperature"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Satisfaction of item
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:grid-aligned"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is outside the scope of this work as it would require an implicit shock-fitting
 approach
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zah18,Cor18"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or a Lagrangian method for chemically reacting flows
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sun20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Item
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:continuous-ratio-of-specific-heats"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represents a special case and is not generally satisfied in multi-component
 flows.
 However, item
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "enu:continuous-temperature"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

