\begin_layout Standard
In this section we present DG discretizations for nonlinear conservation
 laws over a given 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we present DG (semi)-discretization and the temporal discretizat
ion of the multi-dimensional unsteady chemically reacting Navier-Stokes
 equations described in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Chemically-Reacting-Navier-Stokes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, as well as the DG discretization for a one-dimensional system of ordinary
 differential equations (ODEs) as described in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:dg-ode"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Throughout this section, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is partitioned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

, consisting of disjoint sub-domains or cells 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Omega}=\cup_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\overline{\kappa}$
\end_inset

, with interfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 composing a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}}\epsilon=\cup_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\partial\kappa$
\end_inset

, over which an oriented normal 
\begin_inset Formula $n:\epsilon\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 Furthermore, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 consists of two disjoint subsets: the interior interfaces
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{\mathcal{I}}\in\mathcal{E_{I}}=\left\{ \epsilon_{\mathcal{I}}\in\mathcal{E}\middlebar\epsilon_{\mathcal{I}}\cap\partial\Omega=\emptyset\right\} \label{eq:interior-interfaces}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and exterior interfaces 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{\partial}\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial}=\left\{ \epsilon_{\partial}\in\mathcal{E}\middlebar\epsilon_{\partial}\subset\partial\Omega\right\} ,\label{eq:boundary-interfaces}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}=\mathcal{E_{I}}\cup\mathcal{E}_{\partial}$
\end_inset

.
 For interior interfaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\mathcal{I}}\in\mathcal{E_{I}}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{+},\kappa^{-}\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{\mathcal{I}}=\partial\kappa^{+}\cap\partial\kappa^{-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{+},n^{-}$
\end_inset

 denote the outward facing normal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{+},\kappa^{-}$
\end_inset

 respectively, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{+}=-n^{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to discretize the nonlinear conservation laws considered in this
 work, we assume that there is a continuous, invertible mapping
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u:\hat{\Omega}\rightarrow\Omega,\label{eq:shape-mapping}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from a reference domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Omega}\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 to the physical domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

, see
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "Section 2.4.1"
key "Cor20_Ref,Ker20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for additional details.
 We introduce a discrete (finite-dimensional) subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{h}^{p}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 using standard piecewise polynomials, cf.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Har13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}$
\end_inset

 denote the space of polynomials spanned by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with multi-index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{N}_{0}^{d}$
\end_inset

 , satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{d}\alpha_{i}\leq p$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a simplicial grid,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
V_{h}^{p} & = & \left\{ v\in\left[L^{2}\left(\Omega\right)\right]^{m}\middlebar\forall\kappa\in\mathcal{T},\left.v\right|_{\kappa}\circ u\in\left[\mathcal{P}_{p}\right]^{m}\right\} .\label{eq:discrete-subspace-simplex}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Q}_{p}$
\end_inset

 denote the tensor-product space of polynomials spanned by the monomials
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 with multi-index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{N}_{0}^{d}$
\end_inset

 , satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}\leq p$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1\ldots d$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a cuboid grid,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
V_{h}^{p} & = & \left\{ v\in\left[L^{2}\left(\Omega\right)\right]^{m}\middlebar\forall\kappa\in\mathcal{T},\left.v\right|_{\kappa}\circ u\in\left[\mathcal{Q}_{p}\right]^{m}\right\} .\label{eq:discrete-subspace-cubiod}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discretization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Discretization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DG (semi-)discretization of Equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:conservation-law-strong-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:conservation-law-flux-boundary-condition"

\end_inset

 is given as: find 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial y}{\partial t}\in V_{h}^{p}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\kappa}\frac{\partial y}{\partial t}v+\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\partial\kappa}\left(h\left(y,n\right)\right)v^{+}-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\partial\kappa}\average{\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y,\nabla y\right)}\cdot nv^{+}+\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\partial\kappa}\delta\left(y,n\right)v^{+}\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\nonumber \\
+\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\partial\kappa}\left(G\left(y^{+}\right):\left(\average y-y^{+}\right)\otimes n\right)\cdot\nabla v-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\kappa}\mathcal{F}\left(y,\nabla y\right)\cdot\nabla v-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\int_{\kappa}\mathcal{S}\left(y\right)\cdot v=0\qquad\forall v\in V_{h}^{p},\label{eq:semi-discretization-integral}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\left(\frac{\partial y}{\partial t},v\right)_{\kappa}-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\left(\mathcal{F}\left(y,\nabla y\right),\nabla v\right)_{\kappa}+\sum_{\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}}\left(h\left(y,n\right),\left\llbracket v\right\rrbracket \right)_{\mathcal{E}}-\sum_{\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}}\left(\average{\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y,\nabla y\right)}\cdot n-\delta\left(y,n\right),\left\llbracket v\right\rrbracket \right)_{\mathcal{E}}\nonumber \\
+\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\left(G\left(y^{+}\right):\left(\average y-y^{+}\right)\otimes n,\nabla v\right)_{\partial\kappa}-\sum_{\kappa\in\mathcal{T}}\left(\mathcal{S}\left(y\right),v\right)_{\kappa}=0\qquad\forall v\in V_{h}^{p}\:\mathrm{and}\:\forall t\in T,\label{eq:semi-discretization}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cdot,\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes the inner product, 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(y,n\right)$
\end_inset

 is the numerical flux, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(y,n\right)$
\end_inset

 is a penalty term that is required for stability, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\llbracket \cdot\right\rrbracket $
\end_inset

 denotes the jump operator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\average{\cdot}$
\end_inset

 denotes the average operator.
 In this work, the numerical flux chosen to be the HLLC approximate Riemann
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tor13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, see also Appendix B of 
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lv15"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The penalty term 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is implemented via the modified formulation of Bassi and Rebay
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bas98,Bas00,Bas02"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, commonly known as BR2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discrete solution is given by the coefficients of a nodal basis defined
 over each element.
 In this work, the coefficients are defined at the corresponding Gauss-Lobatto
 points of the element.
 In this case, the trace of the solution, i.e., the nodal values at the element
 interface, is readily available and does not require interpolation, therefore,
 pressure equilibrium is trivially maintained across element interfaces.
 The volume and surface terms of Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:semi-discretization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are numerically evaluated using a quadrature free approach
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Atk96,Atk98"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the case of multi-component flows, the evaluation of the nonlinear flux
 presents unique challenges, the details of which are discussed in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:nonlinear-flux-evaluation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On interior interfaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E_{I}}$
\end_inset

, the jump, average, numerical flux, and penalty term are defined in terms
 of the interior and exterior traces, as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\llbracket v\right\rrbracket =v^{+}-v^{-} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E_{I}},\label{eq:jump-interior}\\
\average y=\frac{1}{2}\left(y^{+}+y^{-}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E_{I}},\label{eq:average-state-interior}\\
\average{\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y,\nabla y\right)}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y^{+},\nabla y^{+}\right)+\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y^{-},\nabla y^{-}\right)\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E_{I}},\label{eq:average-flux-interior}\\
h\left(y,n\right)=h\left(y^{+},y^{-},n\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E_{I}},\label{eq:numerical-flux-interior}\\
\delta\left(y,n\right)=\delta\left(y^{+},y^{-},n\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E_{I}}.\label{eq:penalty-term-interior}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the exterior interfaces, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}_{\partial}$
\end_inset

, we define the following,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\llbracket v\right\rrbracket =v^{+} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial},\label{eq:jump-exterior}\\
\average y=y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial},\label{eq:average-state-exterior}\\
\average{\mathcal{F}^{\nu}\left(y,\nabla y\right)}=\mathcal{F}_{\partial}^{\nu}\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial},\label{eq:average-flux-exterior}\\
h\left(y,n\right)=h_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial},\label{eq:numerical-flux-exterior}\\
\delta\left(y,n\right)=\delta_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\partial},\label{eq:penalty-term-exterior}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the prescribed boundary state, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the numerical boundary flux, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\partial}^{\nu}\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+},n^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the viscous boundary flux.
 The numerical and viscous fluxes are defined consistently with the imposed
 boundary condition such that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:conservation-law-flux-boundary-condition"

\end_inset

 is satisfied, cf.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Har13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work we apply the following boundary conditions, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th spatial component of the viscous boundary flux is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\partial,k}^{\nu}\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 , the boundary stress tensor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\partial}=\tau\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

, and boundary heat flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\partial}=q\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

, are both evaluated at the boundary state and the interior gradient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Inflow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inflow boundary condition is specified as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=y_{\infty} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{in}},\label{eq:boundary-state-inflow}\\
\mathcal{F}_{\partial,k}^{\nu}\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right)=\mathcal{F}_{k}^{\nu}\left(y_{\infty},\nabla y^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{in}},\label{eq:boundary-viscous-flux-inflow}\\
h_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=\mathcal{F}^{c}\left(y_{\infty}\right)\cdot n^{+} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{in}},\label{eq:boundary-numerical-flux-inflow}\\
\delta_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=\delta\left(y^{+},y_{\infty}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{in}},\label{eq:boundary-penalty-term-inflow}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\infty}:\Omega\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is a prescribed state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Outflow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We do not restrict the flow at an outflow boundary.
 The boundary condition is therefore given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=y^{+} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{out}},\label{eq:boundary-state-outflow}\\
\mathcal{F}_{\partial,k}^{\nu}\left(y_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right),\nabla y^{+}\right)=\mathcal{F}_{k}^{\nu}\left(y^{+},\nabla y^{+}\right) & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{out}},\label{eq:boundary-viscous-flux-outflow}\\
h_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=\mathcal{F}^{c}\left(y^{+}\right)\cdot n^{+} & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{out}},\label{eq:boundary-numerical-flux-outflow}\\
\delta_{\partial}\left(y^{+},n^{+}\right)=0 & \textup{ on }\epsilon\qquad\forall\epsilon\in\mathcal{E}_{\mathrm{out}}.\label{eq:boundary-penalty-term-outflow}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here the penalty term is evaluated at the interior state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(y^{+},y^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

, which is trivially zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Slip wall:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a slip wall we require the flow be parallel to the boundary.
 We therefore define the boundary velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v_{\partial,1},\ldots,v_{\partial,d}\right):\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

