 onto the span 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi\left(T\right)=\sum_{k}T\left(y\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\label{eq:temperature-projection-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and species concentrations, which interpolate onto the span of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{s}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{i}=\sum_{j}C_{i}\left(x_{j}\right)\varphi_{j}.\label{eq:concentrations-projection-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The pressure, the projection of which is onto the span 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi\left(p\right)=\sum_{k}p\left(y\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\label{eq:pressure-projection-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is defined via
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EOS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and is given in terms of the sum of the concentrations, which is computed
 as
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{i}C_{i} & = & \sum_{i}\sum_{s}C_{i}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(\sum_{s}C_{1}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}+\cdots+\sum_{s}C_{ns}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(C_{1}\left(x_{1}\right)\varphi_{1}+\cdots+C_{1}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}+\cdots+C_{ns}\left(x_{1}\right)\varphi_{1}+\cdots+C_{ns}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(C_{1}\left(x_{1}\right)\varphi_{1}+\cdots+C_{n_{s}}\left(x_{1}\right)\varphi_{1}+\cdots+C_{1}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}+\cdots+C_{ns}\left(x_{s}\right)\varphi_{s}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \left(\left(C_{1}\left(x_{1}\right)+\cdots+C_{n_{s}}\left(x_{1}\right)\right)\varphi_{1}+\cdots+\left(C_{1}\left(x_{s}\right)+\cdots+C_{ns}\left(x_{s}\right)\right)\varphi_{s}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{s}\left(\sum_{i}C_{i}\left(x_{s}\right)\right)\varphi_{s}\label{eq:summed-concentration-projection-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sum_{i}C_{i} & = & \sum_{i}\sum_{j}C_{i}\left(x_{j}\right)\varphi_{j}\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{j}\left(\sum_{i}C_{i}\left(x_{j}\right)\right)\varphi_{j}\label{eq:summed-concentration-projection}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 Furthermore, we introduce a scalar valued test function that interpolates
 onto the span of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
v & =\sum_{q}v\left(x_{q}\right)\varphi_{q}.\label{eq:test-function-interpolation}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Finally, the following linear system can be solved in order to determine
 the expansion coefficients of pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(y\left(x_{r}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\sum_{k}p\left(y\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\sum_{q}v\left(x_{q}\right)\varphi_{q}\right)_{\Omega}=\left(R^{0}\sum_{k}T\left(y\left(x_{k}\right)\varphi_{k}\right)\sum_{j}\left(\sum_{i}C_{j}\left(x_{j}\right)\varphi_{j}\right),\sum_{q}v\left(x_{q}\right)\varphi_{q}\right)_{\Omega}.\label{eq:pressure-projection-linear-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By factoring out the constants and rearranging the sums, we can write the
 resulting system as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{q}v\left(x_{q}\right)\left(\sum_{k}p\left(y\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\left(\varphi_{k},\varphi_{q}\right)_{\Omega}\right)=\sum_{q}v\left(x_{q}\right)\left(R^{0}\sum_{k}T\left(y\left(x_{m}\right)\right)\sum_{j}\left(\sum_{i}C_{i}\left(x_{s}\right)\right)\left(\varphi_{k}\varphi_{j},\varphi_{q}\right)_{\Omega}\right).\label{eq:pressure-projection-linear-system-factored}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This approach is attractive because it will maintain equilibrium within
 an element.
 However, if the temperature or the species concentrations vary within the
 element, the value of pressure can be modified away from the equilibrium
 value as shown in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:pressure-equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 As such, pressure equilibrium between adjacent elements will be lost and
 unphysical pressure oscillations will be generated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both approaches described above result in the loss of equilibrium,
 either with an element or between adjacent elements, we must consider alternati
ve approaches.
 In the case of multi-component flows, we have found the simplest approach
 to work best.
 We project the pressure such that equilibrium is maintained, i.e., into the
 same space as the conserved state, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the pressure projection interpolates onto the span 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{s}\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi\left(p\right)=\sum_{j}p\left(y\left(x_{j}\right)\right)\varphi_{j}.\label{eq:pressure-projection}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Furthermore, the modified flux projection interpolates onto the span of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{r}\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\Pi\left(\mathcal{F}\left(y\right)\right)\right)_{ij}=\sum_{k}\mathcal{F}_{ij}\left(\tilde{y}\left(x_{k}\right)\right)\varphi_{k},\label{eq:flux-projection-modified}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again we have 
\begin_inset Formula $r\ge s$
\end_inset

, and the flux is now evaluated in terms of the modified state 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{y}:\mathbb{R}^{m}\times\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, which is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{y}\left(y,p\right)=\left(\rho v_{1},\ldots,\rho v_{d},\tilde{\rho u}\left(C_{i},\ldots,C_{n_{s}},p\right)+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^{d}\rho v_{k}v_{k},C_{i},\ldots,C_{n_{s}}\right).\label{eq:interpolated-state-modified}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The internal energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\rho u}:\mathbb{R}^{n_{s}}\times\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 , is evaluated from the pressure and the unmodified concentrations as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\rho u}=\sum_{i=1}^{n_{s}}W_{i}C_{i}\sum_{k=0}^{n_{p}}a_{ik}\left(\frac{p}{R^{0}\sum_{i=1}^{n_{s}}C_{i}}\right)^{k}.\label{eq:internal_energy_polynomial-projection}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this way, consistency between the volume and surface terms is preserved
 as well as pressure equilibrium both internally and between adjacent elements.
 A similar conclusion was reached in the context of reconstructed finite
 volume methods where it was found necessary to reconstruct the primitive
 variables, which include velocity and pressure, in order to maintain equilibriu
m at an isolated material or contact discontinuity
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Joh06,Joh11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, in the case of the formulation presented in this work, the above
 analysis applies to all regions of the flow, as the discussion was not
 restricted to the case of an isolated discontinuity, where equilibrium
 is trivially maintained since the primitive variables are readily available
 at the interface, see Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:discrete-pressure-equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

