\begin_layout Subsection
Concluding remarks regarding discrete pressure equilibrium at material interface
s
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Concluding-remarks-pressure-equilibrium"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous Sections we presented several test cases to assess when
 pressure oscillations would be generated for multi-component non-reacting
 flows without physical diffusion.
 Additional stabilization, e.g., artificial viscosity, limiting, or filtering,
 was not applied in any of the test cases to avoid the unintentional suppression
 of pressure oscillations.
 The results confirm the analysis presented in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Discontinuities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and are summarized below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of frozen thermodynamics, unphysical pressure oscillations are
 generated at material interfaces and in smooth regions where mixing occurs,
 requiring additional stabilization, or nonconservative methods.
 The magnitude of the oscillations depends on the method with which 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{p}$
\end_inset

 is evaluated.
 Furthermore, these oscillations are dependent on size of time step and
 grow as the solution evolves, even in smooth regions of the flow, as shown
 in Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:thermal_bubble_delta_p_10_cycles"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast, if the thermodynamics are evaluated exactly, pressure oscillations
 are not generated when the temperature is continuous, regardless of species
 mixing at material interfaces.
 However, pressure oscillations are generated at temperature discontinuities
 but do not cause the solution to diverge, as the oscillations do not grow
 as the solution evolves.
 Finally, pressure oscillations are not generated in regions of sharp continuous
 profiles of species and temperature, as described in Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:thermal-bubble"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we expect the 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{DG}(p>0)$
\end_inset

 formulation for the multi-component reacting Navier-Stokes flows described
 in this work to behave no differently than its counterpart for single-component
 Navier-Stokes flows, namely: high order accuracy is achieved in smooth
 regions of the flow and additional stabilization of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:artifical-viscosity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

